h century. Jean Germain’s Débat du chrétien et du sarrasin -- tThe Extracta ex Alcorano and Giacomo della Marca’s Glosses in MS Falconara 3 -- tThe Glosses on Mark of Toledo’s Alchoranus Latinus -- tDhul-Qarnayn, The One of the Two Horns, in the Latin Glosses to the Qur’an -- tQur’an Quotations in the Liber de Doctrina Mahumet -- tUsing Muslim Exegesis in Europe in the 12th and 18th Centuries: A Comparative Study of Robert of Ketton’s and George Sale’s Approaches -- tRiccoldo da Monte di Croce and the Origins of the Qur’an as a Deviation from Christian Salvation History -- tRiccoldo the Florentine’s Reprobacion del Alcoran: A Manual for Preaching to the ‘Moors’ -- tSicut Euangelia sunt quatuor, distribuerunt continentiam eius in quatuor libros: On the Division of Iberian Qur’ans and Their Translations into Four Parts -- tThe Bellús Qur’an, Martín García, and Martín de Figuerola: The Study of the Qur’an and Its Use in the Sermones de la Fe and the Disputes with Muslims in the Crown of Aragon in the Sixteenth Century -- tConclusion: Robert of Ketton’s Translation and its Legacy -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Manuscript -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1143 Robert of Ketton produced the first Latin translation of the Qur’an. This translation, extant in 24 manuscripts, was one of the main ways in which Latin European readers had access to the Muslim holy book. Yet it was not the only means of transmission of Quranic stories and concepts to the Latin world: there were other medieval translations into Latin of the Qur’an and of Christian polemical texts composed in Arabic which transmitted elements of the Qur’an (often in a polemical mode). The essays in this volume examine the range of medieval Latin transmission of the Qur’an and reaction to the Qur’an by concentrating on the manuscript traditions of medieval Qur’an translations and anti-Islamic polemics in Latin. We see how the Arabic text was transmitted and studied in Medieval Europe. We examine the strategies of translators who struggled to find a proper vocabulary and syntax to render Quranic terms into Latin, at times showing miscomprehensions of the text or willful distortions for polemical purposes. These translations and interpretations by Latin authors working primarily in twelfth- and thirteenth-century Spain were the main sources of information about Islam for European scholars until well into the sixteenth century, when they were printed, reused and commented. This volume presents a key assessment of a crucial chapter in European understandings of Islam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aRELIGION / Islam / Koran & Sacred Writings.2bisacsh  aIslam-Christian relations.  aQuran.  amanuscript studies.  apalaeography.1 aArias Torres, Juan Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiosca i Bas, Antoni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurman, Thomas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasassas Canals, Xavier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCecini, Ulisse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz Palma, Óscar de la, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerrero Hernández, Cándida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerrero Hernández, Cándida, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGlei, Reinhold F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález Muñoz, Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanne, Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJusticia Lara, Agus